s of income to its new capitalist revenues from land sales, subdivision developments, bonds, and rentier income from office, warehousing, and urban-housing properties. Its changing income required new forms of management and the priest-manager was eventually assisted by an accountant, architect, surveyor, clerk, and several notaries and lawyers. The Seminary played a central role in the development of popular schools in Montreal, and in financing and directing social institutions such as hospitals, newspapers, libraries, and national societies, the Seminary of Montreal legitimized the changing class structure of industrializing Montreal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBusiness enterprisesxHistoryxQuébec (Province)xMontréalRegion. 0aBusiness enterpriseszQuébec (Province)zMontréalRegionxHistory. 0aEntreprisesxHistoirexQuébec (Province)xMontréal, Région de. 0aSeigneuriesxHistoirexQuébec (Province)xMontréal, Région de. 0aseigniorial tenurexHistoryxQuébec (Province)xMontréalRegion. 0aseigniorial tenurezQuébec (Province)zMontréalRegionxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356109040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773561090423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773561090/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles